{"title_page": "Jabo people", "text_new": "{{tone|date=December 2019}}\n'''Jabo''' (pronounced {{IPA-xx|\u025f\u02b1\u0251bo|}},<ref>The name has the default tone of the language, tone \"2\", here unmarked.</ref> variant spellings ''Dyabo'', ''Djabo'') is the self-designation of an [[ethnic group]] located in the southeastern part of the [[Liberia|Republic of Liberia]] in [[West Africa]].\nThey have also sometimes referred to themselves as '''[[:#Gweabo|Gweabo]]'''\n<ref>SNG, S&B {{nonspecific|date=November 2018}}r</ref>\nor '''[[:#Nimiah|Nimiah]]''' [[tribe]].<ref>WPA, [Form A]:\"Ancestry --Negro- [Dfabo?] group- Nimi'ab tribe.\"\nWhile at the University of Nebraska, he apparently gave people to understand that his tribe was called '''Nimiah''':  \"One of these students, Charles Blooah, was born in Africa, a member of the aboriginal and cannibalistic Nimiah tribe of Liberia.  At the age of 14 he fled from his tribe in order to escape becoming its king. By 1936 his advancement in education in this country, beginning as an illiterate savage, had reached such a standing that the University of Nebraska awarded him a fellowship In the department of social science.\"  In \"The Negros of Nebraska -- The Negro goes to school\". URL accessed 2006-04-26 [http://www.memoriallibrary.com/NE/Ethnic/Negro/school.htm].  (Blooah died in Colorado, USA, in 1978, a lifelong Methodist.)</ref>\n\nEnglish speakers also use the name of the group for a single member of that group, or for their speech variety.\n\n==Tribe==\nLike many of their neighbors in the area, the Jabo have very pronounced [[ethnocentric]] attitudes,<ref name=\"ETH\">ETH {{nonspecific|date=November 2018}}</ref> and are frequently referred to both by themselves and by others as a ''[[tribe]]'', a term that in Liberia has a meaning imprecise at best.  Confusion may arise due to the circumstance that in Liberia the English word \"tribe\" is also sometimes applied to the second-order administrative \"[[Districts of Liberia|districts]],\" which are not necessarily congruent with \"tribes\" defined in local [[ethnotaxonomy|ethnotaxonomic]] terms.  \"Tribe\" is also occasionally used for a third-order administrative \"clan\" when the latter comprises multiple ethnic [[clans]], as well as for a variety of other more or less ad hoc groups.<ref name=\"tribe\">For a discussion of the use of the term \"tribe\" in Liberia see [http://www.everyculture.com/Ja-Ma/Liberia.html EveryCulture] and also [http://www.globalsecurity.org/military/library/report/1985/liberia_2_ethnic-cat-tribalpeoples.htm GlobalSecurity]</ref>\n\nThe Jabo describe themselves as a \"[[confederation]] of [[tribe]]s.\", or even \"a [[nation]]\".<ref>WPA, p. 1: \"My tribe in Liberia was known as the Djabo Confederacies.\" {{nonspecific|date=November 2018}}</ref>\n<ref>WPA, p. 2: \"So as a result the first family groups formed themselves into Gentile [''i.e.'' clan] group, the Gentile groups into tribes, the tribes into a confederacy, and the confederacy into a nation which we call ---The Djabo.\" {{nonspecific|date=November 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Location==\nThe area inhabited by the Jabo is now mostly in the [[Lower Kru Coast District|Lower Kru Coast district]] of the new (1984) [[Grand Kru County]], with a few outliers across the river in [[Maryland County]].\n\nTheir area coincides more or less with the southern half of [[Lower Kru Coast District]] in [[Grand Kru County]].  This southern portion of the district is defined in terms of Liberian administrative units as the '''Garawe/Nemia''' \"clan\" (code 180810). Jabo territory extends along the coast of southeastern Liberia from Garraway in the northwest proceeding in a southeasterly direction to the Deeah River, and from there inland almost as far as Bewehn.  The northern half of the district is inhabited by the Trembo ethnic group and which has its center at the district capital in Bewehn.\n\n==Population centers==\n\n===Names of towns===\nAt the level below the administrative clan, the Jabo are organized into administrative townships (each with a \"town chief\"), usually consisting of multiple clusters of villages or hamlets.\nHasselbring & Johnson list seven Jabo town complexes:<ref>H&J, 2002, p. 71.{{nonspecific|date=November 2018}}</ref>\n:*Garaway Beach (Polou)\n:*Genoyah\n:*Nemiah (includes: Glopluken, Jlatiken, Mensiengloh, Nyanoken, Penoken, Yaytueken)\n:*Nyambo\n:*Piaty\n:*Poloya (includes: Poloylowen, Pungbaloken, Tuwaken, Weteken)\n:*Weteken\n\nSince the recent civil war in Liberia, many towns have been emptied, renamed, reclaimed, or swollen by displaced populations.\n\n:*Garraway is now called Garraway Beach.\n:*Half Garraway  is now called Yedweke.\n:*(Upper) Nimiah is now called Wilsonville.\n\n===Nimiah===\nThe Jabo population center most reported in the literature is the town complex of Half Garraway (variants: Half Garroway, Half Gadowe, Half Grawe, New Garraway), known in Jabo as '''Nimiah''',\n<ref>Liberian administrative \"clan\" of Garaway/Nemia (area 158.03&nbsp;km\u00b2); see http://humanitarianinfo.org/liberia/mapcentre/reference/country_pdf/LIB046_County_district_and_clan_boundaries_2002_0410%2d03_code_list_short_form_0510%2d03.pdf, p. 4, code #180810.\n</ref>\nwhich is situated  between Garraway and the Seaside [[Grebo people|Grebo]] town of Fishtown (Waa).\n<ref>\n\nGarroway is not to be confused with the similarly named Seaside Grebo towns east of Harper, Cape Palmas.\n</ref>\n\nNimiah consists of two main centers: one village cluster on the coastal lagoon,\nand another, larger cluster located approximately 10&nbsp;km inland.\nThe town on the lagoon (Lower Nimiah, Nimiah Beach) consists of several centers, of which the principal one is now called '''Yedweke''', at latitude  4\u00b028'48\" N (4.48), longitude 7\u00b052'39\" W (-7.8775), altitude  83&nbsp;m (275&nbsp;ft); population 1724.\n\nUpper Nimiah (Nemiah, Nemia, Nimia) is located at Latitude 4\u00b032'40\" N (4.5444), Longitude 7\u00b053'37 W (-7.8936), altitude 101 m (334&nbsp;feet); population 3688.  It is now called '''Wilsonville'''.<ref>See [[gazetteer]]s at http://www.fallingrain.com/world/LI/16/Yedweke.html, et al.</ref>\n\n==Language==\n{{Main|Jabo language}}\nThe Jabo are known for their [[Drum (communication)|drum-signalling system]], which mirrors to some degree the [[Prosody (linguistics)|suprasegmental system]] of their highly [[Tone (linguistics)|tonal]] language.  The collection of their [[proverb]]s and [[saying]]s assembled by Herzog and Blooah<ref name=\"H&B\">H&B</ref> is often cited in the [[Folkloristics|folkloristic]] literature.  The Jabo language is complex and has been studied by well-known [[Linguistics|scientific linguists]].<ref>NST et al. {{nonspecific|date=November 2018}}</ref>\n\n==What's in a name?==\nThe term ''Jabo'' in a narrow sense means \"Ja people\", the ''-bo'' being an animate plural suffix (compare with ''ba'' in '''[[Bantu language|ba-ntu]]''').\nA single member of the group is a ''Jawe''  \"Ja + person\"  and the language *''Jame'' \"Ja + tongue\"(Glebo form {{IPA|[jao\u0129]}}\n.<ref>H&J, pp. 5,66.{{nonspecific|date=November 2018}}</ref>\nThe significative element ''Ja'' is explained as being the proper name of the [[eponym]]ous ancestor of the group.\n<ref>WPA, p. 1: \"My tribe in Liberia was known as the Djabo Confederacies. At first are family or tribe opens with the history of one family. The father of the family was known as the Dja\"{{nonspecific|date=November 2018}}</ref>\n\nCompare:\n:{{IPA|[\u0261\u0361b\u0254\u030fw\u1eb9\u0300]}} \"Glebo man of Fishtown (Waa) clan\"\n:{{IPA|[\u0261\u0361b\u0254\u030fb\u1ecd\u0300]}} \"Glebo people of Fishtown (Waa) clan\"\n\n==Gweabo==\nThe Jabo are also referred to in the literature as the '''Gweabo'''.\nThe Jabo form of the name is {{IPA|[\u0261w\u0205\u0201b\u1ecd\u0300]}}.  This name is also used for them by at least some Glebo speakers as {{IPA|[w\u00e8\u01ceo]}}.\n<ref>H&J, p. 6.{{nonspecific|date=November 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe term is not a mere variant of the word ''Jabo'', as might be assumed.\nIt is, rather, defined as the name of \"a group of five tribes\" or \"a language\".\nIt properly designates a certain [[Patrilineality|patrilineal]] descent group (in this case a \"sub-tribe\"), within the larger group (\"Jabo [[tribe]]\").  It may be conjectured to have as an [[eponym]] the common personal name ''(g)wea''.\n\n''Gweabo'' was originally incorrectly generalized to apply to the larger group (the Jabo confederation) because [[Edward Sapir|Sapir's]] Jabo informant\n<ref>Charles Blooah, b. abt. 1904, d. 30 January 1978, in Colorado.{{nonspecific|date=November 2018}}</ref>\nwas a member of that sub-tribe.\n\nAmong the subdivisions of the Gweabo sub-tribe mentioned in ''Jabo Proverbs from Liberia'' are:\n:*{{IPA|[b\u02b1\u1ecd\u030fl\u1ecd\u0300kw\u1ebd\u0300\u1ebd]}}\n:*{{IPA|[\u0261b\u0254\u030fl\u0254\u0300 \u0261wl\u1ecdbo]}}\n:*{{IPA|[\u0272\u1ea1b\u1ecd\u0301]}}\n\n==Nimiah==\nBlooah sometimes also claimed to be a member of the \"Nimiah tribe;\" sometimes Nimiah was called a township.  As mentioned above, it corresponds to a Liberian administrative clan. The pronunciation in Jabo which was recorded was \n{{IPA|[n\u0129\u0301w\u0324i\u032f\u1eb9\u0303]}}.\n\n==Classification==\nDealing with a people with little recorded history and for which little detailed [[ethnography|ethnographic]] information is available, the most reliable framework for placing them with respect to related peoples is the classification of their language.\n\nJabo clearly belongs within the [[Kru languages|Kru]] family of Niger\u2013Congo languages. For further discussion, see the article [[Grebo people]].\n\n===Jabo and Grebo===\nA certain amount of confusion is created by the fact that many sources treat \"Jabo\" as being either identical with, or as a subgroup of [[Grebo people|Grebo]].  For a discussion of this see the article [[Jabo (language)]].\n\n===Geographical factors===\nAlthough the Jabo area is adjacent to the Seaside Grebo area to the east-southeast, the two are separated by the Deeah (Die or Decoris) River, which is often treacherous and difficult to cross, especially during the rainy season or when a strong tide is running in the estuary.<ref>H&J, pp. 80-81.{{nonspecific|date=November 2018}}</ref>  Because of the lack of usable roads connecting them, the Jabo tend to go northwest to market, into a [[Kru people|Kru]]-oriented area at the county seat of ([[Barclayville]]) and Garraway, north to Bewehn, or sometimes northeast to [[Plibo]], rarely to the commercial and government center in [[Harper, Liberia|Harper]].  This tends to emphasize mutual affinity and intercommunication with the Klao (Krao or \"[[Kru people|Kru]] Proper\"), rather than with the Seaside Grebo.  They are also located in the same newly created (1984) county as the Klao ([[Grand Kru County]]), unlike the Glebo in [[Maryland County]], from which they are once again politically separated.\n\n==Exogamy==\nA cultural trait present among the Jabo, and apparently widespread across the Kru group is the practice of [[virilocality|virilocal]] [[exogamy]].<ref>WPA{{nonspecific|date=November 2018}}</ref>  This is enforced as a [[taboo]] at the clan level, but in practice, many also marry outside their tribe.  The extent of this practice is obviously limited by the difficult transportation situation.<ref>As of 2006-02-25 there were no motorable long- or medium- distance roads in either Grand Kru or Maryland County.  Barclayville, the county seat of Grand Kru County, is inaccessible.[http://www.humanitarianinfo.org/liberia/assessments/others/doc/STATUS%20OF%20ROADS%20IN%20LIBERIA%20AS%20ON%2025%20Jan%202006.pdf_20060313.pdf]</ref>  Nonetheless, the exogamy factor has a certain effect of heightening intergroup awareness and communication.  It remains to be seen how this will be affected by the refugee situation and urbanization.\n\n==Allegations of ritual murder and cannibalism==\nIn researching the literature pertaining to the Jabo, one may occasionally come upon references to them practising [[cannibalism]].  This is not merely a [[canard]] or [[blood libel]].  Charles Blooah, Sapir's Jabo informant, apparently made no secret of the fact.\n\nAgainst the backdrop of widespread violence during the Liberian civil war, reports of ritual murder and cannibalism seem scarcely to rise to the level of newsworthiness.  Yet the inhabitants of the Cape Palmas region have been repeatedly characterized since at least 1668<ref>Liberia: Past and Present: \t\t</ref> as having this practice culturally entrenched among themselves.  Considering the practice's links to Liberian internal politics and secret societies ([[Human leopards|Leopard Men]]), which cut across all social strata, and considering also a sensational legal proceeding in Maryland county in 1977, there is no reason to hope that the practice or its associated belief system has abated or been extirpated.  This is not intended to convey the impression that such practices are limited to this area of [[Africa]] alone.\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n\n==Bibliography==\n[HDS] Herzog, George. \"Drum Signaling in a West African Tribe,\" ''Word'' 1:217-38, 1945.  Reprinted in: ''Language in Culture and Society'', pp.&nbsp;312\u201323. Ed. Dell Hymes.  New York, 1964.\n\n[H&B] Herzog, George, and Charles G. Blooah.  ''Jabo Proverbs from Liberia: Maxims in the Life of a Native Tribe''.  London, Pub. for the International Institute of African Languages & Cultures by Oxford University Press, H. Milford, 1936.\n\n[ETH] Gordon, Raymond G., Jr., editor.  ''Ethnologue: Languages of the World, Fifteenth edition''. Dallas, Tex.: SIL International, 2005. Online version: [http://www.ethnologue.com/].\n\n[I&D] Ingemann, Frances, and John Duitsman.  \"A Survey of Grebo Dialects in Liberia,\" ''Liberian Studies Journal'', 7(2):121\u2013131, 1976.\n\n[JHG] [[Joseph Greenberg|Greenberg, Joseph H.]], ''[[The Languages of Africa]]''.  Indiana Univ. Press, 1966).\n\n[H&J] Hasselbring, Sue and Eric Johnson.  ''A sociolinguistic survey of the Grebo language area of Liberia. SIL Electronic Survey Reports 2002-074'', 2002.  Online version:  [http://www.sil.org/silesr/2002/SILESR2002-074.pdf].\n\n[SNG] [[Edward Sapir|Sapir, Edward]].  \"Notes on the Gweabo Language of Liberia,\" ''Language'', 7:30-41, 1931.\n\n[S&B] [[Edward Sapir|Sapir, Edward]], With Charles G. Blooah.  \"Some Gweabo Proverbs,\" ''Africa'', 2:183-185, 1929.\n\n[NST] [[Nikolai Trubetzkoi|Trubetskoy, Nikolai S.]].  ''Grundz\u00fcge der Phonologie''. (''Principles of Phonology''). ''Travaux du Cercle Linguistique de Prague'', 7).  Prague, 1939.\n\n[WPA] [[Works Progress Administration|WPA]] [[Federal Writers' Project]].  ''Life History Manuscripts from the Folklore Project'', 1936-1940.  Online version: Library of Congress ''American Life Histories: Manuscripts from the Federal Writers' Project, 1936 - 1940'', Item 27 of 312 (Nebraska), \"Charles Blooah\" [http://rs6.loc.gov/ammem/wpaintro/wpahome.html].\n\n==External links==\n*''Maryland in Liberia'', U.S. Navy map from 1853 in the Library of Congress,: [http://memory.loc.gov/cgi-bin/map_item.pl?data=/home/www/data/gmd/gmd8/g8883/g8883m/lm000016.sid&itemLink=r?ammem/gmd:@filreq(@field(NUMBER+@band(g8883m+lm000016))+@field(COLLID+lmmap))&title=Maryland+in+Liberia+/+drawn+under+the+superintendence+of+Com.+Lynch,+U.S.N.,+at+Wm.+Sides+Office,+Balt.&style=lmmap&legend=].\n*Topographic reference map of Grand Kru County as of 2003-09-18: [http://www.humanitarianinfo.org/liberia/mapcentre/topographic/reference/pdf/Grand_Kru.pdf].\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2010}}\n\n{{Ethnic groups in Liberia}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Jabo People}}\n[[Category:Ethnography]]\n[[Category:Ethnic groups in Liberia]]\n[[Category:Cannibalism in Africa]]\n[[Category:Districts of Liberia]]\n", "text_old": "'''Jabo''' (pronounced {{IPA-xx|\u025f\u02b1\u0251bo|}},<ref>The name has the default tone of the language, tone \"2\", here unmarked.</ref> variant spellings ''Dyabo'', ''Djabo'') is the self-designation of an [[ethnic group]] located in the southeastern part of the [[Liberia|Republic of Liberia]] in [[West Africa]].\nThey have also sometimes referred to themselves as '''[[:#Gweabo|Gweabo]]'''\n<ref>SNG, S&B</ref>\nor '''[[:#Nimiah|Nimiah]]''' [[tribe]].<ref>WPA, [Form A]:\"Ancestry --Negro- [Dfabo?] group- Nimi'ab tribe.\"\nWhile at the University of Nebraska, he apparently gave people to understand that his tribe was called '''Nimiah''':  \"One of these students, Charles Blooah, was born in Africa, a member of the aboriginal and cannibalistic Nimiah tribe of Liberia.  At the age of 14 he fled from his tribe in order to escape becoming its king. By 1936 his advancement in education in this country, beginning as an illiterate savage, had reached such a standing that the University of Nebraska awarded him a fellowship In the department of social science.\"  In \"The Negros of Nebraska -- The Negro goes to school\". URL accessed 2006-04-26 [http://www.memoriallibrary.com/NE/Ethnic/Negro/school.htm].  (Blooah died in Colorado, USA, in 1978, a lifelong Methodist.)</ref>\n\nEnglish speakers also use the name of the group for a single member of that group, or for their speech variety.\n\n==Tribe==\nLike many of their neighbors in the area, the Jabo have very pronounced [[ethnocentric]] attitudes,<ref name=\"ETH\">ETH</ref> and are frequently referred to both by themselves and by others as a ''[[tribe]]'', a term that in Liberia has a meaning imprecise at best.  Confusion may arise due to the circumstance that in Liberia the English word \"tribe\" is also sometimes applied to the second-order administrative \"[[Districts of Liberia|districts]],\" which are not necessarily congruent with \"tribes\" defined in local [[ethnotaxonomy|ethnotaxonomic]] terms.  \"Tribe\" is also occasionally used for a third-order administrative \"clan\" when the latter comprises multiple ethnic [[clans]], as well as for a variety of other more or less ad hoc groups.<ref name=\"tribe\">For a discussion of the use of the term \"tribe\" in Liberia see [http://www.everyculture.com/Ja-Ma/Liberia.html EveryCulture] and also [http://www.globalsecurity.org/military/library/report/1985/liberia_2_ethnic-cat-tribalpeoples.htm GlobalSecurity]</ref>\n\nThe Jabo describe themselves as a \"[[confederation]] of [[tribe]]s.\", or even \"a [[nation]]\".<ref>WPA, p. 1: \"My tribe in Liberia was known as the Djabo Confederacies.\"</ref>\n<ref>WPA, p. 2: \"So as a result the first family groups formed themselves into Gentile [''i.e.'' clan] group, the Gentile groups into tribes, the tribes into a confederacy, and the confederacy into a nation which we call ---The Djabo.\"</ref>\n\n==Location==\nThe area inhabited by the Jabo is now mostly in the [[Lower Kru Coast District|Lower Kru Coast district]] of the new (1984) [[Grand Kru County]], with a few outliers across the river in [[Maryland County]].\n\nTheir area coincides more or less with the southern half of [[Lower Kru Coast District]] in [[Grand Kru County]].  This southern portion of the district is defined in terms of Liberian administrative units as the '''Garawe/Nemia''' \"clan\" (code 180810). Jabo territory extends along the coast of southeastern Liberia from Garraway in the northwest proceeding in a southeasterly direction to the Deeah River, and from there inland almost as far as Bewehn.  The northern half of the district is inhabited by the Trembo ethnic group and which has its center at the district capital in Bewehn.\n\n==Population centers==\n\n===Names of towns===\nAt the level below the administrative clan, the Jabo are organized into administrative townships (each with a \"town chief\"), usually consisting of multiple clusters of villages or hamlets.\nHasselbring & Johnson list seven Jabo town complexes:<ref>H&J, 2002, p. 71.</ref>\n:*Garaway Beach (Polou)\n:*Genoyah\n:*Nemiah (includes: Glopluken, Jlatiken, Mensiengloh, Nyanoken, Penoken, Yaytueken)\n:*Nyambo\n:*Piaty\n:*Poloya (includes: Poloylowen, Pungbaloken, Tuwaken, Weteken)\n:*Weteken\n\nSince the recent civil war in Liberia, many towns have been emptied, renamed, reclaimed, or swollen by displaced populations.\n\n:*Garraway is now called Garraway Beach.\n:*Half Garraway  is now called Yedweke.\n:*(Upper) Nimiah is now called Wilsonville.\n\n===Nimiah===\nThe Jabo population center most reported in the literature is the town complex of Half Garraway (variants: Half Garroway, Half Gadowe, Half Grawe, New Garraway), known in Jabo as '''Nimiah''',\n<ref>Liberian administrative \"clan\" of Garaway/Nemia (area 158.03&nbsp;km\u00b2); see http://humanitarianinfo.org/liberia/mapcentre/reference/country_pdf/LIB046_County_district_and_clan_boundaries_2002_0410%2d03_code_list_short_form_0510%2d03.pdf, p. 4, code #180810.\n</ref>\nwhich is situated  between Garraway and the Seaside [[Grebo people|Grebo]] town of Fishtown (Waa).\n<ref>\n\nGarroway is not to be confused with the similarly named Seaside Grebo towns east of Harper, Cape Palmas.\n</ref>\n\nNimiah consists of two main centers: one village cluster on the coastal lagoon,\nand another, larger cluster located approximately 10&nbsp;km inland.\nThe town on the lagoon (Lower Nimiah, Nimiah Beach) consists of several centers, of which the principal one is now called '''Yedweke''', at latitude  4\u00b028'48\" N (4.48), longitude 7\u00b052'39\" W (-7.8775), altitude  83&nbsp;m (275&nbsp;ft); population 1724.\n\nUpper Nimiah (Nemiah, Nemia, Nimia) is located at Latitude 4\u00b032'40\" N (4.5444), Longitude 7\u00b053'37 W (-7.8936), altitude 101 m (334&nbsp;feet); population 3688.  It is now called '''Wilsonville'''.<ref>See [[gazetteer]]s at http://www.fallingrain.com/world/LI/16/Yedweke.html, et al.</ref>\n\n==Language==\n{{Main|Jabo language}}\nThe Jabo are known for their [[Drum (communication)|drum-signalling system]], which mirrors to some degree the [[Prosody (linguistics)|suprasegmental system]] of their highly [[Tone (linguistics)|tonal]] language.  The collection of their [[proverb]]s and [[saying]]s assembled by Herzog and Blooah<ref name=\"H&B\">H&B</ref> is often cited in the [[Folkloristics|folkloristic]] literature.  The Jabo language is complex and has been studied by well-known [[Linguistics|scientific linguists]].<ref>NST et al.</ref>\n\n==What's in a name?==\nThe term ''Jabo'' in a narrow sense means \"Ja people\", the ''-bo'' being an animate plural suffix (compare with ''ba'' in '''[[Bantu language|ba-ntu]]''').\nA single member of the group is a ''Jawe''  \"Ja + person\"  and the language *''Jame'' \"Ja + tongue\"(Glebo form {{IPA|[jao\u0129]}}\n.<ref>H&J, pp. 5,66.</ref>\nThe significative element ''Ja'' is explained as being the proper name of the [[eponym]]ous ancestor of the group.\n<ref>WPA, p. 1: \"My tribe in Liberia was known as the Djabo Confederacies. At first are family or tribe opens with the history of one family. The father of the family was known as the Dja\"</ref>\n\nCompare:\n:{{IPA|[\u0261\u0361b\u0254\u030fw\u1eb9\u0300]}} \"Glebo man of Fishtown (Waa) clan\"\n:{{IPA|[\u0261\u0361b\u0254\u030fb\u1ecd\u0300]}} \"Glebo people of Fishtown (Waa) clan\"\n\n==Gweabo==\nThe Jabo are also referred to in the literature as the '''Gweabo'''.\nThe Jabo form of the name is {{IPA|[\u0261w\u0205\u0201b\u1ecd\u0300]}}.  This name is also used for them by at least some Glebo speakers as {{IPA|[w\u00e8\u01ceo]}}.\n<ref>H&J, p. 6.</ref>\n\nThe term is not a mere variant of the word ''Jabo'', as might be assumed.\nIt is, rather, defined as the name of \"a group of five tribes\" or \"a language\".\nIt properly designates a certain [[Patrilineality|patrilineal]] descent group (in this case a \"sub-tribe\"), within the larger group (\"Jabo [[tribe]]\").  It may be conjectured to have as an [[eponym]] the common personal name ''(g)wea''.\n\n''Gweabo'' was originally incorrectly generalized to apply to the larger group (the Jabo confederation) because [[Edward Sapir|Sapir's]] Jabo informant\n<ref>Charles Blooah, b. abt. 1904, d. January 30, 1978, in Colorado.</ref>\nwas a member of that sub-tribe.\n\nAmong the subdivisions of the Gweabo sub-tribe mentioned in ''Jabo Proverbs from Liberia'' are:\n:*{{IPA|[b\u02b1\u1ecd\u030fl\u1ecd\u0300kw\u1ebd\u0300\u1ebd]}}\n:*{{IPA|[\u0261b\u0254\u030fl\u0254\u0300 \u0261wl\u1ecdbo]}}\n:*{{IPA|[\u0272\u1ea1b\u1ecd\u0301]}}\n\n==Nimiah==\nBlooah sometimes also claimed to be a member of the \"Nimiah tribe;\" sometimes Nimiah was called a township.  As mentioned above, it corresponds to a Liberian administrative clan. The pronunciation in Jabo which was recorded was \n{{IPA|[n\u0129\u0301w\u0324i\u032f\u1eb9\u0303]}}.\n\n==Classification==\nDealing with a people with little recorded history and for which little detailed [[ethnography|ethnographic]] information is available, the most reliable framework for placing them with respect to related peoples is the classification of their language.\n\nJabo clearly belongs within the [[Kru languages|Kru]] family of Niger\u2013Congo languages. For further discussion, see the article [[Grebo people]].\n\n===Jabo and Grebo===\nA certain amount of confusion is created by the fact that many sources treat \"Jabo\" as being either identical with, or as a subgroup of [[Grebo people|Grebo]].  For a discussion of this see the article [[Jabo (language)]].\n\n===Geographical factors===\nAlthough the Jabo area is adjacent to the Seaside Grebo area to the east-southeast, the two are separated by the Deeah (Die or Decoris) River, which is often treacherous and difficult to cross, especially during the rainy season or when a strong tide is running in the estuary.<ref>H&J, pp. 80-81.</ref>  Because of the lack of usable roads connecting them, the Jabo tend to go northwest to market, into a [[Kru people|Kru]]-oriented area at the county seat of ([[Barclayville]]) and Garraway, north to Bewehn, or sometimes northeast to [[Plibo]], rarely to the commercial and government center in [[Harper, Liberia|Harper]].  This tends to emphasize mutual affinity and intercommunication with the Klao (Krao or \"[[Kru people|Kru]] Proper\"), rather than with the Seaside Grebo.  They are also located in the same newly created (1984) county as the Klao ([[Grand Kru County]]), unlike the Glebo in [[Maryland County]], from which they are once again politically separated.\n\n==Exogamy==\nA cultural trait present among the Jabo, and apparently widespread across the Kru group is the practice of [[virilocality|virilocal]] [[exogamy]].<ref>WPA</ref>  This is enforced as a [[taboo]] at the clan level, but in practice, many also marry outside their tribe.  The extent of this practice is obviously limited by the difficult transportation situation.<ref>As of 2006-02-25 there were no motorable long- or medium- distance roads in either Grand Kru or Maryland County.  Barclayville, the county seat of Grand Kru County, is inaccessible.[http://www.humanitarianinfo.org/liberia/assessments/others/doc/STATUS%20OF%20ROADS%20IN%20LIBERIA%20AS%20ON%2025%20Jan%202006.pdf_20060313.pdf]</ref>  Nonetheless, the exogamy factor has a certain effect of heightening intergroup awareness and communication.  It remains to be seen how this will be affected by the refugee situation and urbanization.\n\n==Allegations of ritual murder and cannibalism==\nIn researching the literature pertaining to the Jabo, one may occasionally come upon references to them practising [[cannibalism]].  This is not merely a [[canard]] or [[blood libel]].  Charles Blooah, Sapir's Jabo informant, apparently made no secret of the fact.\n\nAgainst the backdrop of widespread violence during the Liberian civil war, reports of ritual murder and cannibalism seem scarcely to rise to the level of newsworthiness.  Yet the inhabitants of the Cape Palmas region have been repeatedly characterized since at least 1668<ref>Liberia: Past and Present: \t\t</ref> as having this practice culturally entrenched among themselves.  Considering the practice's links to Liberian internal politics and secret societies ([[Human leopards|Leopard Men]]), which cut across all social strata, and considering also a sensational legal proceeding in Maryland county in 1977, there is no reason to hope that the practice or its associated belief system has abated or been extirpated.  This is not intended to convey the impression that such practices are limited to this area of [[Africa]] alone.\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n\n==Bibliography==\n[HDS] Herzog, George. \"Drum Signaling in a West African Tribe,\" ''Word'' 1:217-38, 1945.  Reprinted in: ''Language in Culture and Society'', pp.&nbsp;312\u201323. Ed. Dell Hymes.  New York, 1964.\n\n[H&B] Herzog, George, and Charles G. Blooah.  ''Jabo Proverbs from Liberia: Maxims in the Life of a Native Tribe''.  London, Pub. for the International Institute of African Languages & Cultures by Oxford University Press, H. Milford, 1936.\n\n[ETH] Gordon, Raymond G., Jr., editor.  ''Ethnologue: Languages of the World, Fifteenth edition''. Dallas, Tex.: SIL International, 2005. Online version: [http://www.ethnologue.com/].\n\n[I&D] Ingemann, Frances, and John Duitsman.  \"A Survey of Grebo Dialects in Liberia,\" ''Liberian Studies Journal'', 7(2):121\u2013131, 1976.\n\n[JHG] [[Joseph Greenberg|Greenberg, Joseph H.]], ''[[The Languages of Africa]]''.  Indiana Univ. Press, 1966).\n\n[H&J] Hasselbring, Sue and Eric Johnson.  ''A sociolinguistic survey of the Grebo language area of Liberia. SIL Electronic Survey Reports 2002-074'', 2002.  Online version:  [http://www.sil.org/silesr/2002/SILESR2002-074.pdf].\n\n[SNG] [[Edward Sapir|Sapir, Edward]].  \"Notes on the Gweabo Language of Liberia,\" ''Language'', 7:30-41, 1931.\n\n[S&B] [[Edward Sapir|Sapir, Edward]], With Charles G. Blooah.  \"Some Gweabo Proverbs,\" ''Africa'', 2:183-185, 1929.\n\n[NST] [[Nikolai Trubetzkoi|Trubetskoy, Nikolai S.]].  ''Grundz\u00fcge der Phonologie''. (''Principles of Phonology''). ''Travaux du Cercle Linguistique de Prague'', 7).  Prague, 1939.\n\n[WPA] [[Works Progress Administration|WPA]] [[Federal Writers' Project]].  ''Life History Manuscripts from the Folklore Project'', 1936-1940.  Online version: Library of Congress ''American Life Histories: Manuscripts from the Federal Writers' Project, 1936 - 1940'', Item 27 of 312 (Nebraska), \"Charles Blooah\" [http://rs6.loc.gov/ammem/wpaintro/wpahome.html].\n\n==External links==\n*''Maryland in Liberia'', U.S. Navy map from 1853 in the Library of Congress,: [http://memory.loc.gov/cgi-bin/map_item.pl?data=/home/www/data/gmd/gmd8/g8883/g8883m/lm000016.sid&itemLink=r?ammem/gmd:@filreq(@field(NUMBER+@band(g8883m+lm000016))+@field(COLLID+lmmap))&title=Maryland+in+Liberia+/+drawn+under+the+superintendence+of+Com.+Lynch,+U.S.N.,+at+Wm.+Sides+Office,+Balt.&style=lmmap&legend=].\n*Topographic reference map of Grand Kru County as of 2003-09-18: [http://www.humanitarianinfo.org/liberia/mapcentre/topographic/reference/pdf/Grand_Kru.pdf].\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2010}}\n\n{{Ethnic groups in Liberia}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Jabo People}}\n[[Category:Ethnography]]\n[[Category:Ethnic groups in Liberia]]\n[[Category:Cannibalism in Africa]]\n[[Category:Districts of Liberia]]\n", "name_user": "Dl2000", "label": "safe", "comment": "repair template damage; tidy", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jabo_people"}
{"title_page": "Square One (M-Flo album)", "text_new": "{{About|the M-Flo album|the David Kitt album|David Kitt|[[Blackpink]] single|Square One (single album)}}{{Infobox album\n| name         = Square One\n| type         = studio\n| artist       = [[M-Flo]]\n| cover        = mflo-squareone.jpg\n| alt          = \n| released     = {{start date|2012|03|14}}\n| recorded     = 2011\u20142012\n| venue        = \n| studio       = \n| genre        = {{flatlist|\n* [[Electro house]]\n* [[electropop]]\n* [[drum and bass]]}}\n| length       = 67:51\n| language     = {{flatlist|\n* [[Japanese language|Japanese]]\n* [[English language|English]]}}\n| label        = [[Rhythm Zone]]\n| producer     = M-Flo\n| prev_title   = M-Flo Inside: Works Best IV\n| prev_year    = 2010\n| next_title   = M-Flo DJ Mix: Bon! Enkai\n| next_year    = 2012\n| misc         = {{Singles\n | name        = Square One\n | type        = studio\n | single1     = She's So (Outta Control)\n | single1date = February 29, 2012 <small>(digital download)</small>\n | single2     = Don't Stop Me Now\n | single2date = May 26, 2013 <small>(tour exclusive)</small>\n}}\n}}\n\n'''''Square One''''' is Japanese dance and hip-hop group [[M-Flo]]'s sixth original studio album, released on March 12, 2012.<ref name=\"Neowing\">{{cite web | url=http://www.neowing.co.jp/detailview.html?KEY=RZCD-59030 | title=<nowiki>[CD] SQUARE ONE [CD+DVD] / m-flo</nowiki> |work=Neowing | language=Japanese | accessdate=March 25, 2012}}</ref> It was the group's first studio album in five years, after 2007's ''[[Cosmicolor]]''.\n\n==Background==\n\nIn the time between the release of ''Cosmicolor'' and ''Square One'', M-Flo released two greatest hits albums, ''[[Award Supernova: Loves Best]]'' (2008) and ''MF10: 10th Anniversary Best'' (2009) and two outside collaborations compilation albums, ''M-Flo Inside: Works Best III'' (2009) and ''M-Flo Inside: Works Best IV'' (2010). DJ [[Taku Takahashi]] in 2010 launched his second record label, TCY Recording, featuring a collection of unsigned dance musicians.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.tokyograph.com/news/id-6294 | title=m-flo's Taku launches new label | date=July 1, 2010 | publisher=Tokyo Graph | accessdate=August 13, 2010}}</ref> He also produced the soundtrack for the [[Gainax]] animated series ''[[Panty & Stocking with Garterbelt]]'' in 2010, featuring the dance musicians of his newly formed label.<ref>{{cite web | title=m-flo\u306e\u2606Taku Takahashi\u3001\u30ac\u30a4\u30ca\u30c3\u30af\u30b9\u306e\u65b0\u4f5c\u30a2\u30cb\u30e1\u3067\u97f3\u697d\u3092\u62c5\u5f53 |trans-title=M-Flo's Taku Takahashi in charge of new Gainax anime's soundtrack | url=http://tower.jp/article/news/69649 | work=Tower Records | date=September 9, 2010 | accessdate=September 9, 2010}}</ref> The ''Panty & Stocking with Garterbelt'' [[Panty & Stocking with Garterbelt#Music|soundtrack]] was very successful, becoming the third most sold anime soundtrack in 2011 with 30,000 copies sold.<ref name=\"Mogra\">{{cite web | title=\u79cb\u8449\u539f\u306eMOGRA\u304cm-flo\u306e\u30d1\u30fc\u30c6\u30a3\u3092\u30b8\u30e3\u30c3\u30af!? |trans-title=An M-Flo Party Jacked by Akihabara's Mogra!? | url=http://news.mu-mo.net/view/20091 | work=Mu-Mo | date=December 20, 2011 | accessdate=March 27, 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"OricSubsc\"/>\n\nRapper [[Verbal (rapper)|Verbal]] directed his first music video in 2010, with [[MINMI]]'s \"Patto Hana Saku.\"<ref>{{cite web | title=MINMI\u306ePV\u3092VERBAL\u304c\u521d\u76e3\u7763 |trans-title=Minmi's PV featured Verbal in his directorial debut | url=http://oops-music.com/news.php?nid=59381 | work=Mu-Mo | date=August 27, 2010 | accessdate=March 27, 2012}}</ref> He launched his solo career in 2010 and 2011, with the album ''[[Visionair (album)|Visionair]]'', featuring collaborations with [[Namie Amuro]], [[Lil Wayne]] and [[Nicki Minaj]].<ref>{{cite web | title=VERBAL\u30bd\u30ed\u4f5c\u54c1\u306b\u30ea\u30eb\u30fb\u30a6\u30a7\u30a4\uff06\u5b89\u5ba4\u5948\u7f8e\u6075\u3089\u53c2\u52a0 |trans-title=Verbal Solo Work features Namie Amuro and Lil Wayne | url=http://fmvs.jp/news/music/archive/eid4479.html | work=FMVS | date=February 28, 2011 | accessdate=March 27, 2012}}</ref> Takahashi also debuted with a solo project, under the name The Suitboys, releasing a non-stop DJ mix CD ''After 5 Vol. 1'' in March 2012.\n\nTaku Takahashi created a dance music web radio station called [http://block.fm/ block.fm], featuring Japanese and overseas DJs as radio hosts, including Verbal. The radio station began airing on November 11, 2011.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://m-flo.com/news/taku/20111013.html |title=block.fm |publisher=Artimage |date=October 13, 2011 |accessdate=March 27, 2012 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/66TgzbSNU |archivedate=March 27, 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Conception and writing==\n\nThe album was announced as a third stage in M-Flo's career, featuring [[LISA (Japanese musician, born 1974)|Lisa]] as the group's vocalist between 1998\u20142002, and their \"loves\" era between 2003\u20142008, which featured billed guest vocalists on most of their recordings.<ref name=\"Neowing\"/> For this third stage, M-Flo saw this as a return to their roots,<ref name=\"Neowing\"/> which was the reasoning for the album title, ''Square One''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://m-flo.com/news/m-flo/20120120.html |title=m-flo 5\u5e74\u632f\u308a\u306e\u30cb\u30e5\u30fc\u30a2\u30eb\u30d0\u30e0\u300eSQUARE ONE\u300f3\u670814\u65e5\u30ea\u30ea\u30fc\u30b9\u6c7a\u5b9a!! |trans-title=M-Flo's first new album in five years, ''Square One'', to be released on March 14!! |publisher=Artimage |date=February 29, 2012 |accessdate=March 27, 2012 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/66ThBXzDA |archivedate=March 27, 2012}}</ref> The album was produced without concerns for what the industry or their management were concerned about, which was similar to how M-Flo had pursued their career when they debuted.<ref name=\"TokyoDandyInterview\">{{cite web |url=http://www.tokyodandy.com/interview-with-verbal/ |title='Verbal Exchange' An Interview with Verbal |publisher=Tokyo Dandy |date=March 16, 2012 |accessdate=March 27, 2012 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/66TkrWLJ5 |archivedate=March 27, 2012}}</ref>\n\n''Square One'' took a lot of time to create compared to their previous albums, because Verbal and Taku Takahashi needed to get used to each other's styles and ideas again. Verbal believed that ''Square One'' showed off both of the work in their solo careers strongly.<ref name=\"Vanity-Verbal\">{{cite web | title=m-flo VERBAL VANITYmix 2013 SPRING Cover Interview | url=http://www.vanitymix.jp/music/m-flo-verbal/ | work=Kazuhiro \"Sukao\" Ikeda (Luck'a Inc.) | publisher=Vianity Mix | year=2013 | accessdate=March 16, 2013 |language=Japanese |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6F9yp0JZH |archivedate=March 15, 2012}}</ref>\n\nThe songs were written and produced by M-Flo members [[Taku Takahashi]] and [[Verbal (rapper)|Verbal]]. Eight songs were written in collaboration with fellow Rhythm Zone artist Cream's vocalist, Minami (including the song \"All I Want Is You\"<ref>{{cite web | title=m-flo\u306e20\u5468\u5e74\u8a18\u5ff5\u30ef\u30f3\u30de\u30f3\u306bCrystal Kay\u3001MINMI\u3001JP THE WAVY\u3089\u8c6a\u83ef\u30b2\u30b9\u30c8\u96c6\u7d50 | url=https://natalie.mu/music/news/347576 | publisher=Natalie.mu| date=September 13, 2019 | accessdate=September 14, 2019 |language=Japanese}}</ref>), as well as two songs featuring lyrics by Cream's rapper Staxx T. The song \"Don't Stop Me Now\" featured lyrics former [[Hi-Standard]] vocalist Akihiro Namba, and ''FLJ'' music magazine producer Toshiya Ohno.\n\nWhile the songs feature guest vocalists similar to their ''loves'' albums, the artists names were not announced. Verbal explained the reasoning behind this was that people attach a certain value and preconception to the name of an artist, and would pay more attention to the music itself if the names were not announced.<ref name=\"NatalieInterview\">{{cite web |url=http://natalie.mu/music/pp/m-flo/page/1 |title=Power Push - M-Flo |publisher=Natalie |date=March 19, 2012 |accessdate=March 27, 2012}}</ref>\n\nThe song \"Sure Shot Ricky\" sampled the viral commercial song {{nihongo|\"Sh\u014dsh\u016briki no Uta\"|\u6d88\u81ed\u529b\u306e\u3046\u305f}}, sung by 13-year-old Portuguese boy [[:ja:\u30df\u30b2\u30eb\u30fb\u30b2\u30ec\u30a4\u30ed|Miguel Guerreiro]]. Verbal said the song was chosen as if it were played at a club, it would be a song everyone knows and everyone enjoys.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.musicman-net.com/artist/15941.html |title=\u30df\u30b2\u30eb \u30a2\u30eb\u30d0\u30e0\u300c\u30c1\u30ab\u30e9\u306b\u304b\u3048\u3066\u300d\u6025\u907d\u767a\u58f2\uff06\u6625\u306b\u6765\u65e5\u6c7a\u5b9a |trans-title=Miguel, album ''Chikara ni Kaete'' hurried release and Spring arrival in Japan |publisher=Musicman-Net |date=September 17, 2011 |accessdate=March 27, 2012 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/66TlGTz1H |archivedate=March 27, 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Promotion==\n\nThe song \"Run\" was first performed on September 15, 2011 with [[Mademoiselle Yulia]] at [[Reebok]]'s ''Reethem & Lite'' launch party, when Verbal was chosen as the Asia creative director for Reebok.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://headlines.yahoo.co.jp/hl?a=20110917-00000002-notr-musi |title=VERBAL\u304cReebok\u30a2\u30b8\u30a2\u5730\u57df\u30af\u30ea\u30a8\u30a4\u30c6\u30a3\u30d6\u30fb\u30c7\u30a3\u30ec\u30af\u30bf\u30fc\u306b\u5c31\u4efb! |trans-title=Verbal inaugurated as Reebok's creative director for Asia! |publisher=Yahoo! News Japan |date=September 17, 2011 |accessdate=September 29, 2011 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/623czXKxt |archivedate=September 29, 2011}}</ref>\n\nM-Flo held a concert and DJ event at [[AgeHa]] in [[Koto, Tokyo]] on December 22, 2011 called ''B\u014dnenkai'' (''End-of-Year Party''). The event featured a set with M-Flo's new material, as well as DJs [[Yasutaka Nakata]] ([[Capsule (band)|Capsule]]), [[Fantastic Plastic Machine (musician)|Fantastic Plastic Machine]], and a set with ''Panty & Stocking with Garterbelt'' collaborators [[TeddyLoid]], Hoshina Anniversary and Booty Bronx.<ref name=\"Mogra\"/> The concert featured material from ''Square One'', an excerpt of which was featured on the DVD of the album.\n\n\"She's So (Outta Control)\" was released as the leading track from the album, two weeks before the album's release on February 29, 2012. It is a collaboration with [[South Korea]]n pop/R&B group [[2NE1]] on vocals.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www2.jasrac.or.jp/eJwid/main.jsp?trxID=F20101&WORKS_CD=70434069&subSessionID=001&subSession=start |title=\u4f5c\u54c1\u30b3\u30fc\u30c9  704-3406-9 \uff33\uff28\uff25\u2019\uff33\u3000\uff33\uff2f\uff08\uff2f\uff35\uff34\uff34\uff21\u3000\uff23\uff2f\uff2e\uff34\uff32\uff2f\uff2c\uff09  |trans-title=M-Flo \"She's So(Outta Control)\" tie-up information |publisher=JASRAC |year=2012 |accessdate=March 27, 2012}}</ref> The song reached number 43 on the ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' [[Japan Hot 100]] chart.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.billboard-japan.com/system/jp_charts/hot100/11-50/ |title=Japan Billboard Hot 100 |publisher=Billboard Japan |date=March 21, 2012 |accessdate=March 27, 2012 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/66TmYFSpc |archivedate=March 27, 2012}}</ref> Three music videos were produced for songs on the album: \"She's So (Outta Control),\" as well as the tracks \"All I Want Is You\" and \"Alive.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.spaceshowertv.com/search/detail.cgi?mu=0089176&ch=0 |title=\u30a2\u30fc\u30c6\u30a3\u30b9\u30c8\u540d m-flo \u697d\u66f2\u30bf\u30a4\u30c8\u30eb    She's So (Outta Control) |publisher=Space Shower |year=2012 |accessdate=March 27, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.spaceshowertv.com/search/detail.cgi?mu=0089198&ch=0 |title=\u30a2\u30fc\u30c6\u30a3\u30b9\u30c8\u540d m-flo \u697d\u66f2\u30bf\u30a4\u30c8\u30eb    All I Want Is You |publisher=Space Shower |year=2012 |accessdate=March 27, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.spaceshowertv.com/search/detail.cgi?mu=0089279&ch=0 |title=\u30a2\u30fc\u30c6\u30a3\u30b9\u30c8\u540d m-flo \u697d\u66f2\u30bf\u30a4\u30c8\u30eb    Alive |publisher=Space Shower |year=2012 |accessdate=March 27, 2012}}</ref> Due to digital downloads, the song \"Alive\" debuted at number 81 on the ''Billboard'' Japan Hot 100.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.billboard-japan.com/system/jp_charts/hot100/51-100/ |title=Japan Billboard Hot 100 |publisher=Billboard Japan |date=March 21, 2012 |accessdate=March 27, 2012 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/66TmnsvwW |archivedate=March 27, 2012}}</ref>\n\n12 of the 19 album tracks were released for download on cellphone download provider [[Recochoku]] on February 29, 2012.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://m-flo.com/works/m-flo/20120221.html |title=\u25a02/29(\u6c34) Album\"SQUARE ONE\"\u3088\u308a\u5148\u884c\u914d\u4fe1\uff01 |trans-title=Pre-release songs from album ''Square One'' on February 29 |publisher=Artimage |date=February 21, 2012 |accessdate=March 27, 2012 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/66ThZx2nk |archivedate=March 27, 2012}}</ref>\n\nA special edition of the album was released at [[Culture Convenience Club|Tsutaya]], featuring a bonus CD with \"Let Go (VIP Mix),\" a remix by [[Taku Takahashi]] of their 2006 hit song.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://m-flo.com/news/20120306.html |title=VERBAL\u304cTSUTAYA\u306e1\u65e5\u5e97\u9577\u306b! |trans-title=M-Flo special bonus campaign exclusive to Tsutaya Records |publisher=Artimage |date=March 6, 2012 |accessdate=March 27, 2012 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/66ThjQCZr |archivedate=March 27, 2012}}</ref> Verbal held a special event at [[Shinjuku]]'s Tsutaya store on March 18, 2012 where he acted as the store manager, and will hold another on April 14 at [[Okayama]]'s Tsushima Mall Tsutaya store.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://m-flo.com/news/20120312.html |title=VERBAL\u304cTSUTAYA\u306e1\u65e5\u5e97\u9577\u306b! |trans-title=Verbal, Tsutaya store manager for a day! |publisher=Artimage |date=February 21, 2012 |accessdate=March 12, 2012 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/66TiO2Ml4 |archivedate=March 27, 2012}}</ref>\n\nTwo of the songs featured commercial tie-ups. \"She's So (Outta Control)\" was used as the March 2012 opening theme song for the [[TV Asahi]] show ''Musicru TV'', and was chosen as [[MTV]] Japan's March 2012 ''buzz clip''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://m-flo.com/media/tv/20120228.html |title=m-flo \"She's So(Outta Control)\" \u30bf\u30a4\u30a2\u30c3\u30d7\u60c5\u5831 |trans-title=M-Flo \"She's So(Outta Control)\" tie-up information |publisher=Artimage |date=February 28, 2012 |accessdate=March 27, 2012 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/66ThJR8wQ |archivedate=March 27, 2012}}</ref> \"Don't Stop Me Now\" will be used as the opening theme song for the drama ''Toshidensetsu no Onna'', starring [[Masami Nagasawa]]. The drama began airing on April 13, 2012.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://news.mynavi.jp/c_cobs/news/dogatch/2012/03/m-flo.html |title=m-flo\u304c\u30dc\u30fc\u30ab\u30ea\u30b9\u30c8\u975e\u516c\u958b!?\u300e\u90fd\u5e02\u4f1d\u8aac\u306e\u5973\u300f\u30aa\u30fc\u30d7\u30cb\u30f3\u30b0\u30c6\u30fc\u30de\u66f2\u6c7a\u5b9a!! |trans-title=M-Flo vocalists kept quiet!? Chosen for ''Toshidensetsu no Onna'' opening theme song!! |publisher=MyNavi |date=March 15, 2012 |accessdate=March 27, 2012}}</ref> \"Don't Stop Me Now\" was released as a tour exclusive single at their ''M-Flo Tour 2012 'Square One'''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://ro69.jp/news/detail/68221 |title=m-flo\u3001\u30c4\u30a2\u30fc\u4f1a\u5834\u9650\u5b9a\u30b7\u30f3\u30b0\u30eb\u300cDon't Stop Me Now\u300d\u3092\u30ea\u30ea\u30fc\u30b9 |trans-title=M-Flo released tour exclusive single, 'Don't Stop Me Now' |publisher=Rockin' On |date=May 24, 2012 |accessdate=March 17, 2013}}</ref>\n\nOn May 6, 2012, \"Alive\" was performed live by Verbal and [[Exile (Japanese band)|Exile]]'s [[Atsushi (musician)|Atsushi]] on Exile's weekly television show ''[[:ja:EXILE\u9b42|Exile Tamashii]]''.<ref>{{cite video |people=Verbal, Exile Atsushi |date=May 6, 2012 |title=EXILE\u9b42 [Exile Tamashii] |medium=Television production |language=Japanese |publisher=Mainichi Broadcasting |location=Tokyo, Japan}}</ref>\n\n== Tours ==\n\nM-Flo held a four-date tour Japan, ''M-Flo Tour 2012 'Square One''' in May and June 2012, in the cities [[Chiba, Chiba|Chiba]], [[Fukuoka]], [[Osaka]] and [[Nagoya]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://m-flo.com/news/m-flo/20120229.html |title=m-flo TOUR 2012\u300cSQUARE ONE\u300d\u30c1\u30b1\u30c3\u30c8\u5148\u884c\u4e88\u7d04\u53d7\u4ed8\u4e2d!! |trans-title=M-Flo Tour 2012 'Square One' Preorder Tickets |publisher=Artimage |date=February 29, 2012 |accessdate=March 27, 2012 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/66TgUAKdg |archivedate=March 27, 2012}}</ref>\n\nM-Flo organised the first event at Avex festival [[A-Nation]] for 2012, ''Oto Matsuri'' held on August 3, 2012.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://netokaru.com/?p=7960 |title=m-flo\u3001\u6771\u4eac\u5973\u5b50\u6d41\u3089\u51fa\u6f14\u306e\u300ca-nation\u300d\u30012NE1\u3084\u30a2\u30a4\u30c9\u30ea\u30f3\u30b0!!!\u306a\u3069\u7b2c2\u5f3e\u51fa\u6f14\u8005\u3092\u767a\u8868 |trans-title=M-Flo, Tokyo Girls Style, etc, appearing at A-Nation. 2NE1 and Idoling announced in second round! |publisher=Netokaru |date=May 23, 2012 |accessdate=March 17, 2013}}</ref> They also held their second annual ''Bonenkai'' end-of-year club party, on December 21, 2012, at the club Ageha.<ref>{{cite web | title=m-flo\u30013\u6708\u30a2\u30eb\u30d0\u30e0\uff06\u5148\u884c\u30b7\u30f3\u30b0\u30eb\u306f\u3042\u306e\u4eba\u304c\u6b4c\u3046\u30d0\u30e9\u30fc\u30c9 |trans-title=M-Flo, March album and pre-release single, a ballad with that singer | url=http://natalie.mu/music/news/82905 | work=Natalie | date=January 10, 2013 | accessdate=March 10, 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Track listing==\n\n{{tracklist\n| total_length    = 1:07:51\n| tit