:#afeeee;\"|[[2005 Northern Ireland Trophy|WR]]\n| colspan=\"3\" style=\"text-align:center; color:#ccc;\"| Ranking Event\n| colspan=\"30\" style=\"text-align:center; color:#ccc;\"| Not Held\n|-\n|style=\"background:#EFEFEF;\" | [[Snooker Shoot-Out|Shoot-Out]]\n| colspan=\"18\" style=\"text-align:center; color:#ccc;\"| Tournament Not Held\n|align=\"center\" style=\"background:#afeeee;\"|[[2011 Snooker Shoot-Out|1R]]\n|align=\"center\" style=\"background:#afeeee;\"|[[2012 Snooker Shoot-Out|2R]]\n|}\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size:90%\"\n|-\n|  style=\"text-align:center; color:#ccc;\" colspan=\"4\"|NH / Not Held || event was not held.\n|-\n|  style=\"text-align:center; color:#ccc;\" colspan=\"4\"|NR / Non-Ranking Event || event is/was no longer a ranking event.\n|-\n|  style=\"text-align:center; color:#ccc;\" colspan=\"4\"|R / Ranking Event || event is/was a ranking event.\n|-\n|  style=\"text-align:center; color:#ccc;\" colspan=\"4\"|MR / Minor-Ranking Event || event is/was a minor-ranking event.\n|}\n{{Reflist|group=nb}}\n\n==Career finals==\n===Ranking tournaments: 2 (2 runner-ups)===\n{| class=\"sortable wikitable\"\n!width=\"80\"|Outcome\n!width=\"20\"|No.\n!width=\"50\"|Year\n!style=\"width:150px;\"|Championship\n!style=\"width:170px;\"|Opponent\n!style=\"width:100px;\"|Score\n|-\n| style=\"background:#ffa07a;\"|Runner-up\n| 1.\n| [[2002 British Open (snooker)|2002]]\n| [[British Open (snooker)|British Open]]\n| {{flagicon|ENG}} {{sortname|Paul|Hunter|dab=snooker player}}\n| 4\u20139 \n|-\n| style=\"background:#ffa07a;\"|Runner-up\n| 2.\n| [[2004 Grand Prix (snooker)|2004]]\n| [[World Open (snooker)|Grand Prix]]\n| {{flagicon|ENG}} {{sortname|Ronnie|O'Sullivan}}\n| 5\u20139\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Ian McCulloch}}\n*{{World Snooker|active|13165~2234674,00|name=Ian McCulloch}}\n*\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20100329012326/http://www.global-snooker.com/Ian-McCulloch.asp Profile on Global Snooker]\n*[http://prosnookerblog.com/players/m/ian-mcculloch/ Profile on Pro Snooker Blog]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20081226191217/http://uk.yahoo.eurosport.com/snooker/person_prs28962.shtml Profile on Yahoo! Sport]\n\n<!--Do not \"fix\" this; all Mc/Mac names are sorted as \"Mac\" followed by lower case, per [[WP:MCSTJR]].-->\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:McCulloch, Ian}}\n[[Category:1971 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:English snooker players]]\n[[Category:People from Walton-le-Dale]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2012}}\n{{Use British English|date=July 2012}}\n{{Infobox snooker player\n|name          = Ian McCulloch\n|image         = Ian McCulloch PHC 2011-2.jpg\n|caption       = Paul Hunter Classic 2011\n|birth_date    = {{Birth date and age|1971|7|28|df=y}}\n|birth_place   = [[Walton-le-Dale]], [[City of Preston, Lancashire|Preston]], [[England]] \n|Sport country = {{ENG}}\n|Nickname      = Preston Potter\n|Professional  = 1992\u20132012\n|High ranking  = 16 ([[Snooker world rankings 2005/2006|2005/06]])\n|Prize money   = [[Pound sterling|\u00a3]]608,110\n|High break    = '''145''': <br> <small>2003 British Open</small>\n|Century break = 105  \n|Best finish   = ''Runner-up'' <small>([[2002 British Open (snooker)|2002 British Open]], [[Grand Prix (snooker)|2004 Grand Prix]])</small>\n|Ranking wins = \n}}\n\n'''Ian McCulloch''' (born 28 July 1971) is a former [[English people|English]] professional [[snooker]] player from [[Walton-Le-Dale]], [[City of Preston, Lancashire|Preston]], [[Lancashire]]. He is known for his ability to grind opponents down through protracted safety exchanges and disjointed breakbuilding. He compiled 105 [[century break]]s in his career.<ref name=\"centurybreaks\">{{cite web|title=Centuries|url=http://www.prosnookerblog.com/centuries/|publisher=Pro Snooker Blog|accessdate=5 July 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nMcCulloch turned professional in 1992, and after steadily climbing up the rankings for many years, he reached the quarter-finals of a ranking event for the first time in the [[1999 Welsh Open (snooker)|1999 Welsh Open]]. He also made his debut in the Crucible stages of the [[1999 World Snooker Championship|1999 World Championship]].\n\nLike [[Barry Pinches]] he entered his best form in his early 30s. He reached two ranking event finals \u2013 the [[2002 British Open (snooker)|2002 British Open]] (losing to [[Paul Hunter (snooker player)|Paul Hunter]]) and the [[2004 Grand Prix (snooker)|2004 Grand Prix]] in his home town (losing to [[Ronnie O'Sullivan]]).<ref name=\"Profile on BBC Lancashire\">{{Cite web\n| url = http://www.bbc.co.uk/lancashire/content/articles/2006/03/29/cue_sports_ian_mac_profile.shtml\n| title = Profile on BBC Lancashire\n| publisher = [[BBC]]\n| date = \n| accessdate = 2008-04-02\n}}</ref>\n\nHe beat [[David Gray (snooker player)|David Gray]] to qualify for the [[2003 World Snooker Championship|2003 World Championship]] in a clash between players who share their names with musicians, and went on to reach the quarter finals in [[2004 World Snooker Championship|2004]]. He went one stage further in [[2005 World Snooker Championship|2005]], losing 14&ndash;17 to [[Matthew Stevens]] in the semi-final, beating [[Graeme Dott]], [[Mark Williams (snooker player)|Mark Williams]] and [[Alan McManus]] en route. He was ranked number 16 in the rankings in [[Snooker world rankings 2005/2006|2005/2006 season]], which would normally guarantee a seeding in the ranking tournaments, but was unluckily pushed out by [[Shaun Murphy (snooker player)|Shaun Murphy]], who as the current [[List of world snooker champions|world champion]] was not in top 16 of the rankings, and was seeded before him in tournaments.\n\nHis [[Snooker season 2005/2006|2005/2006 season]] proved disappointing, with a quarter-final appearance in the [[2006 Welsh Open (snooker)|Welsh Open]] the highlight. He failed to qualify for the [[2006 World Snooker Championship|World Championship]], losing to [[Dave Harold]], causing him to drop down the rankings. He made his first appearance as a [[BBC]] pundit during the tournament.\n\nAn improved [[Snooker season 2006/2007|2006/2007]] campaign included a quarter-final run in the [[2006 Grand Prix (snooker)|Grand Prix]]. He qualified for the [[2007 World Snooker Championship|World Championship]], and in the first round he eliminated defending champion Graeme Dott 10&ndash;7, but he lost in the second round 8&ndash;13 to [[Anthony Hamilton (snooker player)|Anthony Hamilton]].\n\nIn the [[2007 UK Championship (snooker)|2007 UK Championship]] he also knocked out the defending champion, by coming from 0&ndash;5 down against [[Peter Ebdon]] to beat him 9&ndash;8 in a remarkable comeback. He lost to [[Stephen Maguire]] 5&ndash;9 in the last 16. He missed out on the [[2008 World Snooker Championship|2008 World Championship]] after losing 5&ndash;10 to eventual quarter-finalist, [[Liang Wenbo]].<ref>[http://www.worldsnooker.com/tournament_news(id19228)-96.htm World Snooker News: ?]  {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080310203158/http://www.worldsnooker.com/tournament_news%28id19228%29-96.htm |date=10 March 2008 }}</ref>\n\nThe [[Snooker season 2008/2009|2008/2009 season]] was a struggle, with only two wins in the first five tournaments. He failed to qualify for the [[2009 World Snooker Championship|World Championship]] again, losing to [[Rory McLeod (snooker player)|Rory McLeod]] despite scoring three centuries. After the 2011/12 season, he decided to quit the game for good after finishing number 68 in the world. This was in part motivated by an occupational shoulder injury.<ref>[http://www.lep.co.uk/sport/other-sports/preston-potter-s-got-no-regrets-1-4717262]</ref> His best run was at the Welsh Open where he reached the final qualifying round before losing to Tom Ford 3-4.\n\nOn 11 October 2009, he won the Bodensee Open, although he was the only professional player taking part.<ref>[http://www.bodensee-open.ch/English/Players.html Bodensee Open: Who plays?] {{Dead link|date=May 2010}}</ref><ref>[https://docs.google.com/viewer?a=v&q=cache:EbNhD0zNPGQJ:www.bodensee-open.ch/Bodensee-Open/Start_files/Final%2520-%2520Tableau%2520-%2520Bodensee-Open%25202009.pdf+Bodensee+2009+McCulloch&hl=en&gl=us&pid=bl&srcid=ADGEESgv_cScPP0x-iMW9dgnAyDRSQSKSbONRhx-KhkJZ_clMTZgx7mzfa3Uq-LvKgWSnotbr8rcG9wIRuGq6-Gu2FXIunVQFfEXrhinUmob3d3QHWDb7T78EmvDPclicVPaKxLV-Z-x&sig=AHIEtbRv89e8zaN4NjmLS7tprrpf3Y4j8A]</ref>\n\n==Broadcasting==\nMcCulloch is a regular pundit for [[William Hill (bookmaker)|William Hill]] and can be heard in their shops previewing Snooker tournaments and as a regular in-studio guest on their In-Play Radio service.\n\n==Performance and rankings timeline==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size:85%;\"\n|- style=\"background:#efefef;\"\n! '''Tournament'''\n! [[Snooker season 1992/1993|1992/<br/>93]]\n! [[Snooker season 1993/1994|1993/<br/>94]]\n! [[Snooker season 1994/1995|1994/<br/>95]]\n! [[Snooker season 1995/1996|1995/<br/>96]]\n! [[Snooker season 1996/1997|1996/<br/>97]]\n! [[Snooker season 1997/1998|1997/<br/>98]]\n! [[Snooker season 1998/1999|1998/<br/>99]]\n! [[Snooker season 1999/2000|1999/<br/>00]]\n! [[Snooker season 2000/2001|2000/<br/>01]]\n! [[Snooker season 2001/2002|2001/<br/>02]]\n! [[Snooker season 2002/2003|2002/<br/>03]]\n! [[Snooker season 2003/2004|2003/<br/>04]]\n! [[Snooker season 2004/2005|2004/<br/>05]]\n! [[Snooker season 2005/2006|2005/<br/>06]]\n! [[Snooker season 2006/2007|2006/<br/>07]]\n! [[Snooker season 2007/2008|2007/<br/>08]]\n! [[Snooker season 2008/2009|2008/<br/>09]]\n! [[Snooker season 2009/2010|2009/<br/>10]]\n! [[Snooker season 2010/2011|2010/<br/>11]]\n! [[Snooker season 2011/2012|2011/<br/>12]]\n|-\n| style=\"background:#EFEFEF;\" | [[Snooker world rankings|Ranking]]<ref name=\"Ranking history\">{{cite web|title=Ranking History|url=http://www.snooker.org/rnk/history.asp|publisher=Snooker.org|accessdate=6 February 2011}}</ref><ref group=\"nb\">From the 2010